[2]
Date: Thu 1 Apr 2004
From: Richard H. Evans <revans@ocvcd.org>

Clarification
--------------
I would like to clarify the posting concerning the finding of West Nile
virus in 2 house finches in Orange County, California. The 2 birds were
positive for specific antibody to West Nile virus using a blocking ELISA to
NS1 protein (Jozan, Evans, et al., Detection of West Nile Virus Infection
in birds in the United States by Blocking ELISA and Immunohistochemistry,
Vector-Borne & Zoonotic Disease 3(3):99-109, 2003).
As part of our >10-year program of wild bird arbovirus serosurveillance,
these finches were trapped, bled, banded, and released. One of the birds
had been trapped and bled a short time earlier and was found seronegative,
indicating a recent seroconversion.
--
Richard H. Evans, DVM, MS
West Nile Virus Surveillence Program
Dr. James Webb Laboratory
Orange County Vector Control District
13001 Garden Grove Blvd.
Garden Grove, CA 92843
<revans@ocvcd.org>
